                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./24: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Nicholson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-31T13:00:00-06:00"
                            >January 31, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9. Department’s circular telegram January 27, 3 p.m. The Acting Foreign
                        Minister<note n="31" xml:id="d349fn1">Antonio Barquero.</note> states that
                    thus far no question in this regard has been received but that in the event his
                    Minister at Washington asks, Nicaragua’s attitude will agree with that of Brazil
                    and the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nicholson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
